#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:3
msgid "NumPy 1.9.0 Release Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:5
msgid "This release supports Python 2.6 - 2.7 and 3.2 - 3.4."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:9
msgid "Highlights"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:10
msgid ""
"Numerous performance improvements in various areas, most notably indexing "
"and operations on small arrays are significantly faster. Indexing operations "
"now also release the GIL."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:13
msgid ""
"Addition of `nanmedian` and `nanpercentile` rounds out the nanfunction set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:17
msgid "Dropped Support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:19
msgid "The oldnumeric and numarray modules have been removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:20
msgid "The doc/pyrex and doc/cython directories have been removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:21
msgid "The doc/numpybook directory has been removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:22
msgid ""
"The numpy/testing/numpytest.py file has been removed together with the "
"importall function it contained."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:27
msgid "Future Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:29
msgid ""
"The numpy/polynomial/polytemplate.py file will be removed in NumPy 1.10.0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:30
msgid ""
"Default casting for inplace operations will change to 'same_kind' in Numpy "
"1.10.0. This will certainly break some code that is currently ignoring the "
"warning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:33
msgid "Relaxed stride checking will be the default in 1.10.0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:34
msgid ""
"String version checks will break because, e.g., '1.9' > '1.10' is True. A "
"NumpyVersion class has been added that can be used for such comparisons."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:36
msgid "The diagonal and diag functions will return writeable views in 1.10.0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:37
msgid ""
"The `S` and/or `a` dtypes may be changed to represent Python strings instead "
"of bytes, in Python 3 these two types are very different."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:42
msgid "Compatibility notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:45
msgid "The diagonal and diag functions return readonly views."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:46
msgid ""
"In NumPy 1.8, the diagonal and diag functions returned readonly copies, in "
"NumPy 1.9 they return readonly views, and in 1.10 they will return writeable "
"views."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:51
msgid "Special scalar float values don't cause upcast to double anymore"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:52
msgid ""
"In previous numpy versions operations involving floating point scalars "
"containing special values ``NaN``, ``Inf`` and ``-Inf`` caused the result "
"type to be at least ``float64``.  As the special values can be represented "
"in the smallest available floating point type, the upcast is not performed "
"anymore."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:58
msgid "For example the dtype of:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:60
msgid "``np.array([1.], dtype=np.float32) * float('nan')``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:62
msgid ""
"now remains ``float32`` instead of being cast to ``float64``. Operations "
"involving non-special values have not been changed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:66
msgid "Percentile output changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:67
msgid ""
"If given more than one percentile to compute numpy.percentile returns an "
"array instead of a list. A single percentile still returns a scalar.  The "
"array is equivalent to converting the list returned in older versions to an "
"array via ``np.array``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:72
msgid ""
"If the ``overwrite_input`` option is used the input is only partially "
"instead of fully sorted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:76
msgid "ndarray.tofile exception type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:77
msgid ""
"All ``tofile`` exceptions are now ``IOError``, some were previously "
"``ValueError``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:81
msgid "Invalid fill value exceptions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:82
msgid "Two changes to numpy.ma.core._check_fill_value:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:84
msgid ""
"When the fill value is a string and the array type is not one of 'OSUV', "
"TypeError is raised instead of the default fill value being used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:87
msgid ""
"When the fill value overflows the array type, TypeError is raised instead of "
"OverflowError."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:91
msgid "Polynomial Classes no longer derived from PolyBase"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:92
msgid ""
"This may cause problems with folks who depended on the polynomial classes "
"being derived from PolyBase. They are now all derived from the abstract base "
"class ABCPolyBase. Strictly speaking, there should be a deprecation "
"involved, but no external code making use of the old baseclass could be "
"found."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:99
msgid "Using numpy.random.binomial may change the RNG state vs. numpy < 1.9"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:100
msgid ""
"A bug in one of the algorithms to generate a binomial random variate has "
"been fixed. This change will likely alter the number of random draws "
"performed, and hence the sequence location will be different after a call to "
"distribution.c::rk_binomial_btpe. Any tests which rely on the RNG being in a "
"known state should be checked and/or updated as a result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:107
msgid "Random seed enforced to be a 32 bit unsigned integer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:108
msgid ""
"``np.random.seed`` and ``np.random.RandomState`` now throw a ``ValueError`` "
"if the seed cannot safely be converted to 32 bit unsigned integers. "
"Applications that now fail can be fixed by masking the higher 32 bit values "
"to zero: ``seed = seed & 0xFFFFFFFF``. This is what is done silently in "
"older versions so the random stream remains the same."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:115
msgid "Argmin and argmax out argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:116
msgid ""
"The ``out`` argument to ``np.argmin`` and ``np.argmax`` and their equivalent "
"C-API functions is now checked to match the desired output shape exactly.  "
"If the check fails a ``ValueError`` instead of ``TypeError`` is raised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:122
msgid "Einsum"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:123
msgid ""
"Remove unnecessary broadcasting notation restrictions. ``np.einsum('ijk,j-"
">ijk', A, B)`` can also be written as ``np.einsum('ij...,j->ij...', A, B)`` "
"(ellipsis is no longer required on 'j')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:128
msgid "Indexing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:130
msgid ""
"The NumPy indexing has seen a complete rewrite in this version. This makes "
"most advanced integer indexing operations much faster and should have no "
"other implications.  However some subtle changes and deprecations were "
"introduced in advanced indexing operations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:135
msgid ""
"Boolean indexing into scalar arrays will always return a new 1-d array. This "
"means that ``array(1)[array(True)]`` gives ``array([1])`` and not the "
"original array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:139
msgid ""
"Advanced indexing into one dimensional arrays used to have (undocumented) "
"special handling regarding repeating the value array in assignments when the "
"shape of the value array was too small or did not match.  Code using this "
"will raise an error. For compatibility you can use ``arr.flat[index] = "
"values``, which uses the old code branch.  (for example ``a = np.ones(10); "
"a[np.arange(10)] = [1, 2, 3]``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:146
msgid ""
"The iteration order over advanced indexes used to be always C-order. In "
"NumPy 1.9. the iteration order adapts to the inputs and is not guaranteed "
"(with the exception of a *single* advanced index which is never reversed for "
"compatibility reasons). This means that the result is undefined if multiple "
"values are assigned to the same element.  An example for this is ``arr[[0, "
"0], [1, 1]] = [1, 2]``, which may set ``arr[0, 1]`` to either 1 or 2."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:154
msgid ""
"Equivalent to the iteration order, the memory layout of the advanced "
"indexing result is adapted for faster indexing and cannot be predicted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:157
msgid ""
"All indexing operations return a view or a copy. No indexing operation will "
"return the original array object. (For example ``arr[...]``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:160
msgid ""
"In the future Boolean array-likes (such as lists of python bools) will "
"always be treated as Boolean indexes and Boolean scalars (including python "
"``True``) will be a legal *boolean* index. At this time, this is already the "
"case for scalar arrays to allow the general ``positive = a[a > 0]`` to work "
"when ``a`` is zero dimensional."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:166
msgid ""
"In NumPy 1.8 it was possible to use ``array(True)`` and ``array(False)`` "
"equivalent to 1 and 0 if the result of the operation was a scalar.  This "
"will raise an error in NumPy 1.9 and, as noted above, treated as a boolean "
"index in the future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:171
msgid ""
"All non-integer array-likes are deprecated, object arrays of custom integer "
"like objects may have to be cast explicitly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:174
msgid ""
"The error reporting for advanced indexing is more informative, however the "
"error type has changed in some cases. (Broadcasting errors of indexing "
"arrays are reported as ``IndexError``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:178
msgid "Indexing with more then one ellipsis (``...``) is deprecated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:181
msgid "Non-integer reduction axis indexes are deprecated"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:182
msgid ""
"Non-integer axis indexes to reduction ufuncs like `add.reduce` or `sum` are "
"deprecated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:186
msgid "``promote_types`` and string dtype"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:187
msgid ""
"``promote_types`` function now returns a valid string length when given an "
"integer or float dtype as one argument and a string dtype as another "
"argument.  Previously it always returned the input string dtype, even if it "
"wasn't long enough to store the max integer/float value converted to a "
"string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:194
msgid "``can_cast`` and string dtype"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:195
msgid ""
"``can_cast`` function now returns False in \"safe\" casting mode for integer/"
"float dtype and string dtype if the string dtype length is not long enough "
"to store the max integer/float value converted to a string. Previously "
"``can_cast`` in \"safe\" mode returned True for integer/float dtype and a "
"string dtype of any length."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:202
msgid "astype and string dtype"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:203
msgid ""
"The ``astype`` method now returns an error if the string dtype to cast to is "
"not long enough in \"safe\" casting mode to hold the max value of integer/"
"float array that is being casted. Previously the casting was allowed even if "
"the result was truncated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:209
msgid "`npyio.recfromcsv` keyword arguments change"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:210
msgid ""
"`npyio.recfromcsv` no longer accepts the undocumented `update` keyword, "
"which used to override the `dtype` keyword."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:214
msgid "The ``doc/swig`` directory moved"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:215
msgid "The ``doc/swig`` directory has been moved to ``tools/swig``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:218
msgid "The ``npy_3kcompat.h`` header changed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:219
msgid ""
"The unused ``simple_capsule_dtor`` function has been removed from "
"``npy_3kcompat.h``.  Note that this header is not meant to be used outside "
"of numpy; other projects should be using their own copy of this file when "
"needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:225
msgid ""
"Negative indices in C-Api ``sq_item`` and ``sq_ass_item`` sequence methods"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:226
msgid ""
"When directly accessing the ``sq_item`` or ``sq_ass_item`` PyObject slots "
"for item getting, negative indices will not be supported anymore. "
"``PySequence_GetItem`` and ``PySequence_SetItem`` however fix negative "
"indices so that they can be used there."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:232
msgid "NDIter"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:233
msgid ""
"When ``NpyIter_RemoveAxis`` is now called, the iterator range will be reset."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:235
msgid ""
"When a multi index is being tracked and an iterator is not buffered, it is "
"possible to use ``NpyIter_RemoveAxis``. In this case an iterator can shrink "
"in size. Because the total size of an iterator is limited, the iterator may "
"be too large before these calls. In this case its size will be set to ``-1`` "
"and an error issued not at construction time but when removing the multi "
"index, setting the iterator range, or getting the next function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:242
msgid ""
"This has no effect on currently working code, but highlights the necessity "
"of checking for an error return if these conditions can occur. In most cases "
"the arrays being iterated are as large as the iterator so that such a "
"problem cannot occur."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:247 ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:448
msgid "This change was already applied to the 1.8.1 release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:250
msgid "``zeros_like`` for string dtypes now returns empty strings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:251
msgid ""
"To match the `zeros` function `zeros_like` now returns an array initialized "
"with empty strings instead of an array filled with `'0'`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:256
msgid "New Features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:259
msgid "Percentile supports more interpolation options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:260
msgid ""
"``np.percentile`` now has the interpolation keyword argument to specify in "
"which way points should be interpolated if the percentiles fall between two "
"values.  See the documentation for the available options."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:265
msgid "Generalized axis support for median and percentile"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:266
msgid ""
"``np.median`` and ``np.percentile`` now support generalized axis arguments "
"like ufunc reductions do since 1.7. One can now say axis=(index, index) to "
"pick a list of axes for the reduction. The ``keepdims`` keyword argument was "
"also added to allow convenient broadcasting to arrays of the original shape."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:272
msgid "Dtype parameter added to ``np.linspace`` and ``np.logspace``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:273
msgid ""
"The returned data type from the ``linspace`` and ``logspace`` functions can "
"now be specified using the dtype parameter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:277
msgid "More general ``np.triu`` and ``np.tril`` broadcasting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:278
msgid ""
"For arrays with ``ndim`` exceeding 2, these functions will now apply to the "
"final two axes instead of raising an exception."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:282
msgid "``tobytes`` alias for ``tostring`` method"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:283
msgid ""
"``ndarray.tobytes`` and ``MaskedArray.tobytes`` have been added as aliases "
"for ``tostring`` which exports arrays as ``bytes``. This is more consistent "
"in Python 3 where ``str`` and ``bytes`` are not the same."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:288
msgid "Build system"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:289
msgid "Added experimental support for the ppc64le and OpenRISC architecture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:292
msgid "Compatibility to python ``numbers`` module"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:293
msgid ""
"All numerical numpy types are now registered with the type hierarchy in the "
"python ``numbers`` module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:297
msgid "``increasing`` parameter added to ``np.vander``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:298
msgid ""
"The ordering of the columns of the Vandermonde matrix can be specified with "
"this new boolean argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:302
msgid "``unique_counts`` parameter added to ``np.unique``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:303
msgid ""
"The number of times each unique item comes up in the input can now be "
"obtained as an optional return value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:307
msgid "Support for median and percentile in nanfunctions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:308
msgid ""
"The ``np.nanmedian`` and ``np.nanpercentile`` functions behave like the "
"median and percentile functions except that NaNs are ignored."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:312
msgid "NumpyVersion class added"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:313
msgid ""
"The class may be imported from numpy.lib and can be used for version "
"comparison when the numpy version goes to 1.10.devel. For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:316
msgid ""
">>> from numpy.lib import NumpyVersion\n"
">>> if NumpyVersion(np.__version__) < '1.10.0'):\n"
"...     print('Wow, that is an old NumPy version!')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:321
msgid "Allow saving arrays with large number of named columns"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:322
msgid ""
"The numpy storage format 1.0 only allowed the array header to have a total "
"size of 65535 bytes. This can be exceeded by structured arrays with a large "
"number of columns. A new format 2.0 has been added which extends the header "
"size to 4 GiB. `np.save` will automatically save in 2.0 format if the data "
"requires it, else it will always use the more compatible 1.0 format."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:329
msgid "Full broadcasting support for ``np.cross``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:330
msgid ""
"``np.cross`` now properly broadcasts its two input arrays, even if they have "
"different number of dimensions. In earlier versions this would result in "
"either an error being raised, or wrong results computed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:336
msgid "Improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:339
msgid "Better numerical stability for sum in some cases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:340
msgid ""
"Pairwise summation is now used in the sum method, but only along the fast "
"axis and for groups of the values <= 8192 in length. This should also "
"improve the accuracy of var and std in some common cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:345
msgid "Percentile implemented in terms of ``np.partition``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:346
msgid ""
"``np.percentile`` has been implemented in terms of ``np.partition`` which "
"only partially sorts the data via a selection algorithm. This improves the "
"time complexity from ``O(nlog(n))`` to ``O(n)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:351
msgid "Performance improvement for ``np.array``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:352
msgid ""
"The performance of converting lists containing arrays to arrays using ``np."
"array`` has been improved. It is now equivalent in speed to ``np."
"vstack(list)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:357
msgid "Performance improvement for ``np.searchsorted``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:358
msgid ""
"For the built-in numeric types, ``np.searchsorted`` no longer relies on the "
"data type's ``compare`` function to perform the search, but is now "
"implemented by type specific functions. Depending on the size of the inputs, "
"this can result in performance improvements over 2x."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:364
msgid "Optional reduced verbosity for np.distutils"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:365
msgid ""
"Set ``numpy.distutils.system_info.system_info.verbosity = 0`` and then calls "
"to ``numpy.distutils.system_info.get_info('blas_opt')`` will not print "
"anything on the output. This is mostly for other packages using numpy."
"distutils."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:371
msgid "Covariance check in ``np.random.multivariate_normal``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:372
msgid ""
"A ``RuntimeWarning`` warning is raised when the covariance matrix is not "
"positive-semidefinite."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:376
msgid "Polynomial Classes no longer template based"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:377
msgid ""
"The polynomial classes have been refactored to use an abstract base class "
"rather than a template in order to implement a common interface. This makes "
"importing the polynomial package faster as the classes do not need to be "
"compiled on import."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:383
msgid "More GIL releases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:384
msgid ""
"Several more functions now release the Global Interpreter Lock allowing more "
"efficient parallelization using the ``threading`` module. Most notably the "
"GIL is now released for fancy indexing, ``np.where`` and the ``random`` "
"module now uses a per-state lock instead of the GIL."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:390
msgid "MaskedArray support for more complicated base classes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:391
msgid ""
"Built-in assumptions that the baseclass behaved like a plain array are being "
"removed. In particular, ``repr`` and ``str`` should now work more reliably."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:396 ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:439
msgid "C-API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:400
msgid "Deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:403
msgid "Non-integer scalars for sequence repetition"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:404
msgid ""
"Using non-integer numpy scalars to repeat python sequences is deprecated. "
"For example ``np.float_(2) * [1]`` will be an error in the future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:408
msgid "``select`` input deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:409
msgid ""
"The integer and empty input to ``select`` is deprecated. In the future only "
"boolean arrays will be valid conditions and an empty ``condlist`` will be "
"considered an input error instead of returning the default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:414
msgid "``rank`` function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:415
msgid ""
"The ``rank`` function has been deprecated to avoid confusion with ``numpy."
"linalg.matrix_rank``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:419
msgid "Object array equality comparisons"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:420
msgid ""
"In the future object array comparisons both `==` and `np.equal` will not "
"make use of identity checks anymore. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:427
msgid ""
"will consistently return False (and in the future an error) even if the "
"array in `a` and `b` was the same object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:430
msgid ""
"The equality operator `==` will in the future raise errors like `np.equal` "
"if broadcasting or element comparisons, etc. fails."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:433
msgid ""
"Comparison with `arr == None` will in the future do an elementwise "
"comparison instead of just returning False. Code should be using `arr is "
"None`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:436
msgid ""
"All of these changes will give Deprecation- or FutureWarnings at this time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.9.0-notes.rst:441
msgid ""
"The utility function npy_PyFile_Dup and npy_PyFile_DupClose are broken by "
"the internal buffering python 3 applies to its file objects. To fix this two "
"new functions npy_PyFile_Dup2 and npy_PyFile_DupClose2 are declared in "
"npy_3kcompat.h and the old functions are deprecated. Due to the fragile "
"nature of these functions it is recommended to instead use the python API "
"when possible."
msgstr ""
